---

<DocsLayout
  title="Snowflake ML scoring"
  description="Per-row ML inference fanned out to 500 Burla workers against a Snowflake table."
  lede="The canonical 'why I wanted dbt-burla' workload — run an ML model across every row of a big Snowflake table, in parallel, from inside a dbt Python model. No Snowpark, no Databricks."
  crumbs={[{ title: "Examples", href: withBase("/examples/") }]}
  toc={toc}
  prev={{ title: "DuckDB quickstart", href: withBase("/examples/quickstart-duckdb/") }}
  next={{ title: "BigQuery LLM enrichment", href: withBase("/examples/bigquery-llm-enrichment/") }}
>
  <h2 id="setup">Setup</h2>
  <Code code={`pip install "dbt-burla[snowflake]"
cd dbt-burla/examples/02-snowflake-ml-scoring
cp profiles.example.yml profiles.yml
$EDITOR profiles.yml`} lang="bash" theme="github-light" />
  <p>Make sure <code>burla login</code> is configured (or set <code>burla_fake: true</code> in <code>profiles.yml</code> to run in-process against your Snowflake).</p>

  <h2 id="run">Run it</h2>
  <Code code={`dbt run --profiles-dir .`} lang="bash" theme="github-light" />

  <h2 id="the-model">The model</h2>
  <Code code={`# models/scored_customers.py
import math

import pandas as pd
from burla import remote_parallel_map


def score(row: dict) -> dict:
    """Runs on one Burla worker for one customer row."""
    spend = float(row["total_spend"] or 0)
    orders = int(row["order_count"] or 0)
    recency = int(row["days_since_last_order"] or 365)
    churn_score = 1 - math.exp(-recency / 90) + 0.1 * math.exp(-orders / 5)
    return {**row, "churn_score": round(min(churn_score, 1.0), 4)}


def model(dbt, session):
    dbt.config(
        materialized="table",
        burla_workers=500,
        burla_cpus_per_worker=2,
        # Bake your model + deps into a custom image:
        # burla_image="us-docker.pkg.dev/my-proj/my-model:latest",
    )

    customers = dbt.ref("stg_customers").to_dict("records")
    scored = list(remote_parallel_map(score, customers))
    return pd.DataFrame(scored)`} lang="python" theme="github-light" />
  <p>In a real project, <code>score()</code> would load a cached scikit-learn / XGBoost / PyTorch model (from GCS, S3, or baked into <code>burla_image</code>) and call <code>.predict()</code>.</p>

  <h2 id="tuning">Tuning</h2>
  <table>
    <thead><tr><th>Config</th><th>When to change it</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>burla_workers</code></td><td>Scale up for faster wall-clock time. Scale down to stay under cost budgets or rate limits.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>burla_cpus_per_worker</code></td><td>More CPUs for multi-threaded inference; 1-2 is usually fine for scikit-learn / XGBoost.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>burla_ram_per_worker</code></td><td>Bump if your model artifact + row batch exceeds default RAM.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>burla_image</code></td><td>Bake the model + exact dependencies in. Sub-second cold starts.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="dataflow">Data flow</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Pull:</strong> <code>SELECT * FROM stg_customers</code> → pandas DataFrame on the dbt runner.</li>
    <li><strong>Ship:</strong> rows + the <code>model()</code> function are cloudpickled and sent to Burla.</li>
    <li><strong>Score:</strong> each row is passed to <code>score()</code> on a Burla worker (workers process batches in parallel).</li>
    <li><strong>Land:</strong> result DataFrame is uploaded back to Snowflake via <code>write_pandas</code>, staged, then atomically swapped.</li>
  </ol>
</DocsLayout>
